  "editorial": {
    "title": "Recursive Insertion Sort Analysis",
    "intuition": "The problem requires sorting an array of integers using the recursive insertion sort algorithm. The intuition behind this approach is to break down the array into smaller subarrays and sort each one recursively, ultimately merging the sorted subarrays into a single sorted array.",
    "bruteForce": "The brute force approach involves using the recursive insertion sort algorithm as given, which has a time complexity of O(N^2) due to the nested loops and recursive calls. This approach is correct but slow for large inputs, as it involves a significant amount of repeated work.",
    "betterSolution": "A better solution would involve optimizing the recursive insertion sort algorithm to reduce the number of comparisons and swaps required. However, given the constraints of the problem, the recursive insertion sort algorithm is the most suitable approach.",
    "optimalSolution": "The optimal solution involves using the recursive insertion sort algorithm with a slight optimization, where the recursive call is made for the subarray excluding the last element, and then the last element is inserted into its correct position in the sorted subarray. This approach has a time complexity of O(N^2) and a space complexity of O(N), making it the most efficient solution for this problem.",
    "proofOfCorrectness": "The proof of correctness for the recursive insertion sort algorithm involves showing that the algorithm maintains the invariant that the subarray from index 0 to n-1 is sorted after each recursive call. This can be proven using mathematical induction, where the base case is when n is 1, and the inductive step involves showing that if the subarray from index 0 to n-2 is sorted, then the subarray from index 0 to n-1 is also sorted after the recursive call and the insertion of the last element.",
    "dryRun": "A dry run of the algorithm involves walking through the steps of the algorithm with a sample input, such as the array [5, 2, 4, 6, 1, 3]. This helps to visualize the recursive calls and the insertion of elements into their correct positions.",
